{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7aad84de-63ca-4f7f-8417-5536ed13ddec","content":"PID 12345 doesn't appear to be running on this machine. But here's exactly how to diagnose and configure dumps:\n\n## 1. Determine Runtime Type\n\nRun these against your actual PID:\n\n```bash\n# If this shows loaded shared libraries like libcoreclr.so → CoreCLR\ncat /proc/<PID>/maps | grep -E 'libcoreclr|libclrjit'\n\n# If NO coreclr libs are found → likely NativeAOT (single static binary)\n# Confirm with:\nreadelf -p .comment /proc/<PID>/exe 2>/dev/null\n```\n\n**Quick rule:** CoreCLR loads `libcoreclr.so` and `libclrjit.so`. NativeAOT is a self-contained binary with no CLR shared libraries.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR apps\n\nSet these environment variables before launching the app:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT apps\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the CoreCLR dump infrastructure. Use the **Linux kernel** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Set dump path pattern\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Or use systemd-coredump if available\necho '|/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump %P %u %g %s %t %c %h' | \\\n  sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n```\n\n### For either runtime (belt-and-suspenders)\n\nYou can safely set **both** — the CoreCLR env vars are ignored by NativeAOT, and `ulimit -c unlimited` works for both:\n\n```bash\n# Works regardless of runtime\nulimit -c unlimited\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Analyzing Dumps\n\n| Runtime   | Tool                          |\n|-----------|-------------------------------|\n| CoreCLR   | `dotnet-dump analyze <file>`  |\n| NativeAOT | `gdb` or `lldb` (no SOS/DAC) |\n\nRun the `/proc/<PID>/maps` check on your actual process and I can give you more specific guidance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0fce58c6-47ca-40c0-b5d3-b9dfc8b68830","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist (PID 12345). This is expected — the user gave a hypothetical PID. Let me provide them with the diagnostic steps and configuration guidance directly.","outputTokens":755,"requestId":"4185:195805:62D5B57:6C2152C:69F16513"},"id":"a07f82a6-4534-43f8-aace-57aabfd7095e","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:55:47.606Z","parentId":"ffa91b88-f34f-417a-9f9f-14daa7495bd1"}
